{"variants":[{"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}],"paths":["\/documentation\/mm4"]}],"metadata":{"externalID":"MM4","modules":[{"name":"MM4"}],"title":"MM4","roleHeading":"Framework","role":"collection","symbolKind":"module"},"sections":[],"hierarchy":{"paths":[[]]},"primaryContentSections":[{"content":[{"level":2,"type":"heading","text":"Overview","anchor":"Overview"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The simulator supports the atoms enumerated by ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4AtomCode","isActive":true},{"text":", with some","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"restrictions on permitted bond types. Elements except C, Si, Ge must have"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"every covalent bond shared with a carbon atom. In addition, no dissimilar"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"non-H\/C atoms may be separated by a bond once removed. Within these"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"restrictions, there exists a large variety of permissible structures, more"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"than with exclusively carbon and hydrogen.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"All force terms from MM3, and most terms from MM4, are included, except:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Electronegativity effect correction to equilibrium bond angle","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Electronegativity effect correction to bond stretching stiffness"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Torsion-torsion interaction","type":"text"}]}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Bend-torsion-bend interaction in bulk diamond","type":"text"}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"All major platforms (Mac, Linux, Windows) and all major GPU architectures"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"(Apple, AMD, Intel, Nvidia) are supported. This includes multi-GPU systems","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"with up to around a dozen GPUs (e.g. a single supercomputer node). This is"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"because it delegates all of the computation to OpenMM, an existing,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"well-tested framework for easily porting molecular simulation algorithms to"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"multiple vendors. OpenMM avoids any O(n^3) algorithms and provides the"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"flexibility to opt out of O(n^2) algorithms. For example, the","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4ForceField\/minimize(tolerance:maxIterations:)","isActive":true,"overridingTitle":"minimizer","overridingTitleInlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"minimizer"}]},{"type":"text","text":""},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"uses limited-memory BFGS with O(n) complexity."}]},{"style":"note","name":"Note","type":"aside","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Throughout the entire software stack, from setup to minimization to"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"simulation, this simulator is O(n). Linear scaling exists at every system","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"size and material composition. This is a rarity among simulation","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"algorithms, most of which are inherently O(n^2) or"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/xtb-docs.readthedocs.io\/en\/latest\/gfnff.html","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":"."},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"MM4 is one of the few simulation techniques that can simulate","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"supermassive million-atom nanosystems on affordable hardware. There are","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"ideas about O(n) game physics-like simulators employing static"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"analysis, which can significantly reduce the constant factor to linear"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"scaling. However, there are not yet any verified implementations that"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"project the inherently digital nanoscale onto a macroscale continuous"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"(analog) representation."}]}]},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This is an NVE simulator, using 32-bit single precision and a massive"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"timestep. Energy is not conserved to the precision of kT. It fluctuates","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"wildly, but shouldn’t systematically drift upward or downward (unless the","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"timestep exceeds C-H stretching resonance frequency). The default"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"timestep (4 fs) is so massive that integration error dwarfs numerical"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"error. Even if the forcefield used 64-bit double or mixed precision, that"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"would not improve its ability to conserve energy."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"style":"note","name":"Note","content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Accuracy (whether an archer hits the right target) is orthogonal"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"to precision (whether the arrows hit the same place every time).","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"Conservation of energy only affects the number of significant figures of","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"measured energy (precision). It does not make system dynamics more"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"accurate, except in the case where energy systematically drifts upward."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"type":"aside"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The integrator uses a multiple time-stepping (MTS) scheme. Cheaper bonded"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"forces, such as bond-stretch and bond-bend, are only stable at ~2 fs"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"without constraints. Expensive forces like torsions, nonbonded, and"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"electrostatic can execute at double the timestep. The value you enter for"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4ForceField\/timeStep","type":"reference","overridingTitleInlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"timeStep"}],"isActive":true,"overridingTitle":"timeStep"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"specifies the execution rate of expensive forces. Always","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"assume the C-H stretching forces execute at half the specified timestep.","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"For example, in the note below, bond stretching forces don’t actually"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"execute at the quoted ‘2 fs’."}]},{"style":"note","type":"aside","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"To maximize the simulation speed, hydrogen mass repartitioning (HMR)","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"is enabled by default. This method makes hydrogens heaver and makes","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"non-hydrogen atoms lighter, to decrease the C-H\/Si-H\/Ge-H stretching"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"frequency. You can, and should, disable HMR for energy-conserving","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"simulations where timestep falls below 2 fs. This can be done by setting","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4ParametersDescriptor\/hydrogenMassScale"},{"type":"text","text":" to "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"1"},{"type":"text","text":"."},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"Note that changing the repartitioning will shift the center of mass,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"which is where bulk angular momentum is applied."}]}],"name":"Note"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Single precision is an implementation choice to make the simulator more"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"compatible with different GPU architectures. Most vendors have no or few","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"FP64 units (unlike CPU, where FP64 is widely supported). Mixed precision","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"can sometimes run the bulk of computations in FP32, with only the energy"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"computations in FP64. However, even mixed precision has implementation","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"issues, being difficult to run on GPUs with zero FP64 units.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The best method to maximize energy conservation is a timestep of 1 fs."},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"This requires 4x as much computation for the same trajectory length,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"compared to the default (4 fs). It executes expensive forces at 1 fs and"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"cheap forces at 0.5 fs. Integration error scales O(h^2), so this should be","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"around 16x more precise. Any smaller timestep, and rounding error from","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"FP32 will overtake integration error."}]}],"kind":"content"}],"kind":"symbol","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"The MM2 force field used to create "},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"Nanosystems (1992)","type":"text"}]},{"type":"text","text":", but updated with"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"modern ab initio calculations."}],"topicSections":[{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4ForceField","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4State"],"title":"Classes"},{"title":"Structures","identifiers":["doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4Address","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4AngleExtendedParameters","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4AngleParameters","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4Angles","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4AtomParameters","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4Atoms","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4BondExtendedParameters","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4BondParameters","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4Bonds","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4ForceFieldDescriptor","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4ForceFieldEnergy","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4ForceOptions","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4Parameters","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4ParametersDescriptor","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4RigidBody","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4Rings","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4StateDescriptor","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4TorsionExtendedParameters","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4TorsionParameters","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4Torsions"]},{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4AJPerKJPerMol","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4AJPerZJ","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4AmuPerYg","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4BoltzInKJPerMolPerK","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4BoltzInZJPerK","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4DebyePerEAngstrom","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4EAngstromPerDebye","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4KJPerMolPerAJ","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4KJPerMolPerZJ","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4VectorWidth","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4YgPerAmu","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4ZJPerAJ","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4ZJPerKJPerMol"],"title":"Variables"},{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4DoubleVector","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4FloatVector","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4Int16Vector","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4Int32Vector","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4Int64Vector","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4Int8Vector","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4UInt16Vector","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4UInt32Vector","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4UInt64Vector","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4UInt8Vector"],"title":"Type Aliases"},{"identifiers":["doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4AtomCode","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4CenterType","doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4Error"],"title":"Enumerations"}],"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"schemaVersion":{"minor":3,"patch":0,"major":0},"references":{"doc://MM4/documentation/MM4/MM4AtomCode":{"identifier":"doc:\/\/MM4\/documentation\/MM4\/MM4AtomCode","title":"MM4AtomCode","fragments":[{"text":"enum","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"MM4AtomCode","kind":"identifier"}],"navigatorTitle":[{"text":"MM4AtomCode","kind":"identifier"}],"role":"symbol","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"MM4 codes for an element or an atom in a specific functional group."}],"url":"\/documentation\/mm4\/mm4atomcode","kind":"symbol","type":"topic"},"doc://MM4/documentation/MM4/MM4ForceField":{"abstract":[{"text":"A force field simulator.","type":"text"}],"role":"symbol","fragments":[{"text":"class","kind":"keyword"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"text":"MM4ForceField","kind":"identifier"}],"title":"MM4ForceField","kind":"symbol","type":"topic","navigatorTitle":[{"text":"MM4ForceField","kind":"identifier"}],"url":"\/documentation\/mm4\/mm4f